I see your point. AssertInitializedOrInitializingInThread actually contains 2 CHECKS, each one with a specific failure message giving information known at runtime like the class' status. If I go the IsInitializedOrInitializingInThread route, I'd need to move these failure messages to a separate function to dump it with the DCHECK. Assuming the method's class is in "declaring_class" variable, I'd write something like "DCHECK(declaring_class->IsInitializedOrInitializingInThread(thread)) << class->DumpInitializationCheckFailureMessage(thread);". If you prefer this way, it's fine to me

Note we already have Thread::AssertThreadSuspensionIsAllowable as sanity check for debug build. It's a bit more complex than AssertInitializedOrInitializingInThread though.

